<doc id="250323" wikidata="Q332648" url="?curid=250323" title="Covering space">
<text>In topology, a covering or covering projection is a map between topological spaces that, intuitively, locally acts like a projection of multiple copies of a space onto itself. In particular, coverings are special types of local homeomorphisms. If formula_1 is a covering, formula_2 is said to be a covering space or cover of formula_3, and formula_3 is said to be the base of the covering, or simply the base. By abuse of terminology, formula_5 and formula_6 may sometimes be called covering spaces as well. Since coverings are local homeomorphisms, a covering space is a special kind of étalé space.

Covering spaces first arose in the context of complex analysis (specifically, the technique of analytic continuation), where they were introduced by Riemann as domains on which naturally multivalued complex functions become single-valued. These spaces are now called Riemann surfaces.

Covering spaces are an important tool in several areas of mathematics. In modern geometry, covering spaces (or branched coverings, which have slightly weaker conditions) are used in the construction of manifolds, orbifolds, and the morphisms between them. In algebraic topology, covering spaces are closely related to the fundamental group: for one, since all coverings have the homotopy lifting property, covering spaces are an important tool in the calculation of homotopy groups. A standard example in this vein is the calculation of the fundamental group of the circle by means of the covering of formula_7 by formula_8 (see below). Under certain conditions, covering spaces also exhibit a Galois correspondence with the subgroups of the fundamental group. 

== Definition ==

Let formula_3 be a topological space. A covering of formula_3 is a continuous map
: formula_11
such that for every formula_12 there exists an open neighborhood formula_13 of formula_14 and a discrete space formula_15 such that formula_16 and formula_17 is a homeomorphism for every formula_18.
The open sets formula_19 are called sheets, which are uniquely determined up to homeomorphism if formula_13 is connected. For each formula_12 the discrete set formula_22 is called the fiber of formula_14. If formula_3 is connected (and formula_5 is non-empty), it can be shown that formula_26 is surjective, and the cardinality of formula_15 is the same for all formula_12; this value is called the degree of the covering. If formula_5 is path-connected, then the covering formula_30 is called a path-connected covering. This definition is equivalent to the statement that formula_26 is a locally trivial Fiber bundle.

Some authors also require that formula_26 be surjective in the case that formula_3 is not connected.

== Examples ==
* For every topological space formula_3, the identity map formula_35 is a covering. Likewise for any discrete space formula_36 the projection formula_37 taking formula_38 is a covering. Coverings of this type are called trivial coverings; if formula_36 has finitely many (say formula_40) elements, the covering is called the trivial &quot;formula_40-sheeted&quot; covering of formula_3. 

* The map formula_43 with formula_44 is a covering of the unit circle formula_7. The base of the covering is formula_7 and the covering space is formula_8. For any point formula_48 such that formula_49, the set formula_50 is an open neighborhood of formula_14. The preimage of formula_52 under formula_53 is 
*: formula_54 
: and the sheets of the covering are formula_55 for formula_56 The fiber of formula_14 is
:: formula_58 
* Another covering of the unit circle is the map formula_59 with formula_60 for some formula_61 For an open neighborhood formula_52 of an formula_63, one has: 
:: formula_64.
* A map which is a local homeomorphism but not a covering of the unit circle is formula_65 with formula_66. There is a sheet of an open neighborhood of formula_67, which is not mapped homeomorphically onto formula_52.

== Properties ==
=== Local homeomorphism ===
Since a covering formula_69 maps each of the disjoint open sets of formula_70 homeomorphically onto formula_52 it is a local homeomorphism, i.e. formula_26 is a continuous map and for every formula_73 there exists an open neighborhood formula_74 of formula_75, such that formula_76 is a homeomorphism.

It follows that the covering space formula_77 and the base space formula_3 locally share the same properties.

* If formula_3 is a connected and non-orientable manifold, then there is a covering formula_80 of degree formula_81, whereby formula_5 is a connected and orientable manifold.
* If formula_3 is a connected Lie group, then there is a covering formula_80 which is also a Lie group homomorphism and formula_85 is a Lie group.
* If formula_3 is a graph, then it follows for a covering formula_69 that formula_77 is also a graph.
* If formula_3 is a connected manifold, then there is a covering formula_80, whereby formula_5 is a connected and simply connected manifold.
* If formula_3 is a connected Riemann surface, then there is a covering formula_80 which is also a holomorphic map and formula_5 is a connected and simply connected Riemann surface.

=== Factorisation ===
Let formula_95 and formula_77 be path-connected, locally path-connected spaces, and formula_97 and formula_53 be continuous maps, such that the diagram 

commutes.

* If formula_6 and formula_100 are coverings, so is formula_53.
* If formula_6 and formula_53 are coverings, so is formula_100.

=== Product of coverings ===
Let formula_3 and formula_106 be topological spaces and formula_107 and formula_108 be coverings, then formula_109 with formula_110 is a covering. However, coverings of formula_111 are not all of this form in general.

=== Equivalence of coverings ===
Let formula_3 be a topological space and formula_107 and formula_114 be coverings. Both coverings are called equivalent, if there exists a homeomorphism formula_115, such that the diagram

commutes. If such a homeomorphism exists, then one calls the covering spaces formula_77 and formula_117 isomorphic.

=== Lifting property ===
All coverings satisfy the lifting property, i.e.:

Let formula_118 be the unit interval and formula_107 be a covering. Let formula_120 be a continuous map and formula_121 be a lift of formula_122, i.e. a continuous map such that formula_123. Then there is a uniquely determined, continuous map formula_124 for which formula_125 and which is a lift of formula_126, i.e. formula_127.

If formula_3 is a path-connected space, then for formula_129 it follows that the map formula_130 is a lift of a path in formula_3 and for formula_132 it is a lift of a homotopy of paths in formula_3.

As a consequence, one can show that the fundamental group formula_134 of the unit circle is an infinite cyclic group, which is generated by the homotopy classes of the loop formula_135 with formula_136.

Let formula_3 be a path-connected space and formula_107 be a connected covering. Let formula_139 be any two points, which are connected by a path formula_140, i.e. formula_141 and formula_142. Let formula_143 be the unique lift of formula_140, then the map 
: formula_145 with formula_146

is bijective.

If formula_3 is a path-connected space and formula_148 a connected covering, then the induced group homomorphism 
: formula_149 with formula_150,
is injective and the subgroup formula_151 of formula_152 consists of the homotopy classes of loops in formula_3, whose lifts are loops in formula_77.

== Branched covering ==
=== Definitions ===
==== Holomorphic maps between Riemann surfaces ====
Let formula_3 and formula_156 be Riemann surfaces, i.e. one dimensional complex manifolds, and let formula_157 be a continuous map. formula_158 is holomorphic in a point formula_12, if for any charts formula_160 of formula_14 and formula_162 of formula_163, with formula_164, the map formula_165 is holomorphic.

If formula_158 is holomorphic at all formula_12, we say formula_158 is holomorphic.

The map formula_169 is called the local expression of formula_158 in formula_12.

If formula_157 is a non-constant, holomorphic map between compact Riemann surfaces, then formula_158 is surjective and an open map, i.e. for every open set formula_174 the image formula_175 is also open.

==== Ramification point and branch point ====
Let formula_157 be a non-constant, holomorphic map between compact Riemann surfaces. For every formula_12 there exist charts for formula_14 and formula_163 and there exists a uniquely determined formula_180, such that the local expression formula_126 of formula_158 in formula_14 is of the form formula_184. The number formula_185 is called the ramification index of formula_158 in formula_14 and the point formula_12 is called a ramification point if formula_189. If formula_190 for an formula_12, then formula_14 is unramified. The image point formula_193 of a ramification point is called a branch point.

==== Degree of a holomorphic map ====
Let formula_157 be a non-constant, holomorphic map between compact Riemann surfaces. The degree formula_195 of formula_158 is the cardinality of the fiber of an unramified point formula_193, i.e. formula_198.

This number is well-defined, since for every formula_199 the fiber formula_200 is discrete and for any two unramified points formula_201, it is: formula_202

It can be calculated by: 
