== Universal covering ==

=== Definition ===
Let formula_216 be a simply connected covering. If formula_217 is another simply connected covering, then there exists a uniquely determined homeomorphism formula_218, such that the diagram

commutes.

This means that formula_6 is, up to equivalence, uniquely determined and because of that universal property denoted as the universal covering of the space formula_3.

=== Existence ===
A universal covering does not always exist. The following theorem guarantees its existence for a certain class of base spaces.

Let formula_3 be a connected, locally simply connected topological space. Then, there exists a universal covering formula_222

The set formula_5 is defined as formula_224 where formula_225 is any chosen base point. The map formula_226 is defined by formula_227

The topology on formula_5 is constructed as follows: Let formula_229 be a path with formula_230 Let formula_52 be a simply connected neighborhood of the endpoint formula_232 Then, for every formula_233 there is a path formula_234 inside formula_52 from formula_14 to formula_237 that is unique up to homotopy. Now consider the set formula_238 The restriction formula_239 with formula_240 is a bijection and formula_241 can be equipped with the final topology of formula_242

The fundamental group formula_243 acts freely on formula_5 by formula_245 and the orbit space formula_246 is homeomorphic to formula_3 through the map formula_248

=== Examples ===
* formula_43 with formula_44 is the universal covering of the unit circle formula_7.
* formula_252 with formula_253 is the universal covering of the projective space formula_254 for formula_255.
* formula_256 with formula_257 is the universal covering of the unitary group formula_258.
* Since formula_259, it follows that the quotient map formula_260 is the universal covering of formula_261.
* A topological space which has no universal covering is the Hawaiian earring: formula_262 One can show that no neighborhood of the origin formula_263 is simply connected.

== G-coverings ==
Let &quot;G&quot; be a discrete group acting on the topological space &quot;X&quot;. This means that each element &quot;g&quot; of &quot;G&quot; is associated to a homeomorphism H&quot;g&quot; of &quot;X&quot; onto itself, in such a way that H&quot;g&quot; &quot;h&quot; is always equal to H&quot;g&quot; ∘ H&quot;h&quot; for any two elements &quot;g&quot; and &quot;h&quot; of &quot;G&quot;. (Or in other words, a group action of the group &quot;G&quot; on the space &quot;X&quot; is just a group homomorphism of the group &quot;G&quot; into the group Homeo(&quot;X&quot;) of self-homeomorphisms of &quot;X&quot;.) It is natural to ask under what conditions the projection from &quot;X&quot; to the orbit space &quot;X&quot;/&quot;G&quot; is a covering map. This is not always true since the action may have fixed points. An example for this is the cyclic group of order 2 acting on a product by the twist action where the non-identity element acts by . Thus the study of the relation between the fundamental groups of &quot;X&quot; and &quot;X&quot;/&quot;G&quot; is not so straightforward.

However the group &quot;G&quot; does act on the fundamental groupoid of &quot;X&quot;, and so the study is best handled by considering groups acting on groupoids, and the corresponding &quot;orbit groupoids&quot;. The theory for this is set down in Chapter 11 of the book &quot;Topology and groupoids&quot; referred to below. The main result is that for discontinuous actions of a group &quot;G&quot; on a Hausdorff space &quot;X&quot; which admits a universal cover, then the fundamental groupoid of the orbit space &quot;X&quot;/&quot;G&quot; is isomorphic to the orbit groupoid of the fundamental groupoid of &quot;X&quot;, i.e. the quotient of that groupoid by the action of the group &quot;G&quot;. This leads to explicit computations, for example of the fundamental group of the symmetric square of a space.

== Smooth coverings ==
Let and be smooth manifolds with or without boundary. A covering formula_264 is called a smooth covering if it is a smooth map and the sheets are mapped &quot;diffeomorphically&quot; onto the corresponding open subset of . (This is in contrast to the definition of a covering, which merely requires that the sheets are mapped &quot;homeomorphically&quot; onto the corresponding open subset.)

== Deck transformation ==
=== Definition ===
Let formula_107 be a covering. A deck transformation is a homeomorphism formula_266, such that the diagram of continuous maps

commutes. Together with the composition of maps, the set of deck transformation forms a group formula_267, which is the same as formula_268.

Now suppose formula_269 is a covering map and formula_270 (and therefore also formula_3) is connected and locally path connected. The action of formula_268 on each fiber is free. If this action is transitive on some fiber, then it is transitive on all fibers, and we call the cover regular (or normal or Galois). Every such regular cover is a principal, where formula_273 is considered as a discrete topological group.

Every universal cover formula_274 is regular, with deck transformation group being isomorphic to the fundamental group 

=== Examples ===
* Let formula_59 be the covering formula_60 for some formula_277, then the map formula_278 for formula_279 is a deck transformation and formula_280.
* Let formula_43 be the covering formula_44, then the map formula_283 for formula_279 is a deck transformation and formula_285.
* As another important example, consider formula_286 the complex plane and formula_287 the complex plane minus the origin. Then the map formula_288 with formula_289 is a regular cover. The deck transformations are multiplications with formula_211-th roots of unity and the deck transformation group is therefore isomorphic to the cyclic group formula_291. Likewise, the map formula_292 with formula_293 is the universal cover.

=== Properties ===
Let formula_3 be a path-connected space and formula_107 be a connected covering. Since a deck transformation formula_266 is bijective, it permutes the elements of a fiber formula_297 with formula_12 and is uniquely determined by where it sends a single point. In particular, only the identity map fixes a point in the fiber. Because of this property every deck transformation defines a group action on formula_77, i.e. let formula_174 be an open neighborhood of a formula_12 and formula_302 an open neighborhood of an formula_303, then formula_304 is a group action.

