== Galois correspondence ==
Let formula_3 be a connected and locally simply connected space, then for every subgroup formula_389 there exists a path-connected covering formula_390 with formula_391.

Let formula_392 and formula_393 be two path-connected coverings, then they are equivalent iff the subgroups formula_394 and formula_395 are conjugate to each other.

Let formula_3 be a connected and locally simply connected space, then, up to equivalence between coverings, there is a bijection:

formula_397

For a sequence of subgroups formula_398 one gets a sequence of coverings formula_399. For a subgroup formula_400 with index formula_401, the covering formula_402 has degree formula_214.

== Classification ==
=== Definitions ===
==== Category of coverings ====
Let formula_3 be a topological space. The objects of the category formula_405 are the coverings formula_107 of formula_3 and the morphisms between two coverings formula_107 and formula_409 are continuous maps formula_410, such that the diagram 

commutes.

==== G-Set ====
Let formula_411 be a topological group. The category formula_412 is the category of sets which are G-sets. The morphisms are G-maps formula_413 between G-sets. They satisfy the condition formula_414 for every formula_415.

=== Equivalence ===
Let formula_3 be a connected and locally simply connected space, formula_12 and formula_418 be the fundamental group of formula_3. Since formula_411 defines, by lifting of paths and evaluating at the endpoint of the lift, a group action on the fiber of a covering, the functor formula_421 is an equivalence of categories.

== Applications ==
An important practical application of covering spaces occurs in charts on SO(3), the rotation group. This group occurs widely in engineering, due to 3-dimensional rotations being heavily used in navigation, nautical engineering, and aerospace engineering, among many other uses. Topologically, SO(3) is the real projective space RP3, with fundamental group Z/2, and only (non-trivial) covering space the hypersphere &quot;S&quot;3, which is the group Spin(3), and represented by the unit quaternions. Thus quaternions are a preferred method for representing spatial rotations – see quaternions and spatial rotation.

However, it is often desirable to represent rotations by a set of three numbers, known as Euler angles (in numerous variants), both because this is conceptually simpler for someone familiar with planar rotation, and because one can build a combination of three gimbals to produce rotations in three dimensions. Topologically this corresponds to a map from the 3-torus &quot;T&quot;3 of three angles to the real projective space RP3 of rotations, and the resulting map has imperfections due to this map being unable to be a covering map. Specifically, the failure of the map to be a local homeomorphism at certain points is referred to as gimbal lock, and is demonstrated in the animation at the right – at some points (when the axes are coplanar) the rank of the map is 2, rather than 3, meaning that only 2 dimensions of rotations can be realized from that point by changing the angles. This causes problems in applications, and is formalized by the notion of a covering space.

